## Étapes d'implémentation

### Étape 1 — Migration DB

Créer une table dédiée `oauth_tokens` (pas de nouvelle colonne dans `profile`).

**Fichier :** `back/migrations/044_add_outlook_token.sql`

```sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS "public"."oauth_tokens" (
    "user_id" uuid NOT NULL,
    "provider" text NOT NULL,
    "service" text NOT NULL,
    "token_json" text NOT NULL,
    "scope" text,
    "expires_at" timestamptz,
    "created_at" timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    "updated_at" timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    PRIMARY KEY ("user_id", "provider", "service")
);
```

Ajouter `back/schema/tables/oauth_tokens.sql`.

---

### Étape 2 — Client Microsoft Graph

**Fichier :** `back/src/infrastructure/clients/outlook_client.py`

Classe `OutlookClient` (analogue à `GmailClient`) :
- Attributs : `access_token`, `refresh_token`, `expires_at`, `client_id`, `client_secret`, `tenant`, `token_saver`
- `_refresh_if_needed()` — vérifie `expires_at`, si expiré appelle le token endpoint avec `grant_type=refresh_token`, appelle `token_saver(new_token_dict)`
- `get_profile()` — `GET https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/me` → retourne `{displayName, mail, userPrincipalName}`
- `list_messages(max_results)` — `GET https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/me/messages?$top={max_results}&$select=id,subject,from,receivedDateTime,bodyPreview`
- `send_message(to, subject, body)` — `POST https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/me/sendMail`

Token stocké comme JSON (dict) dans `oauth_tokens.token_json` pour (`provider=microsoft`, `service=mail`) :
```json
{
  "access_token": "...",
  "refresh_token": "...",
  "expires_at": 1234567890,
  "token_type": "Bearer",
  "scope": "Mail.Read Mail.Send offline_access"
}
```

Fonctions utilitaires (niveau module, miroir de `azure_client.py`) :

```python
def get_outlook_oauth_url(redirect_url=None, user_id=None) -> dict:
    # Scopes email : Mail.Read Mail.Send offline_access
    # State signé (HMAC) + expiration courte + nonce
    # Retourne {status: "ok", auth_url: "https://login.microsoftonline.com/..."}

def handle_outlook_oauth_callback(code, state=None) -> dict:
    # Échange code → tokens (POST token endpoint)
    # Décode/valide state → user_id, redirect_url
    # Retourne {status: "ok", tokens: {...}, user_id, redirect_url}
```

